      <h2>Why These 10 Bhajans</h2>
      <p>These 10 bhajans were selected based on three criteria: melodic simplicity (using 5-7 swaras), cultural familiarity (known by most Indian learners), and pedagogical value (each teaches a new melodic skill). Together they cover bhajans for different deities, different emotional moods, and progressively wider melodic ranges — giving you a rounded devotional repertoire.</p>

      <h2>1. Raghupati Raghav Raja Ram</h2>
      <p>Uses: Sa Re Ga Ma Pa. Sthayi notation: P P P D P, M G R S. This Gandhi-associated Ram bhajan is the ideal first bhajan. Its melody uses only 5 swaras stays in a comfortable range and has strong rhythmic feel. Practice at 80 BPM in Keherwa taal (8 beats). Once comfortable add the antara: S G M P, G M P D N S.</p>

      <h2>2. Om Jai Jagdish Hare</h2>
      <p>Uses: Sa Re Ga Ma Pa Dha Ni. Opening: S S S R G, M M G R S. This lakshmi puja aarti is known across all of India. The melody rises to Ni making it slightly more challenging than Raghupati Raghav. Practice the two main melodic sections separately before connecting. Works beautifully as harmonium practice because it demonstrates how Ni adds emotional depth.</p>

      <h2>3. Vaishnav Jan To</h2>
      <p>Uses: Sa Re Ga Ma Pa Dha Ni upper-Sa. Opening: S G M P, D N upper-S. This classic Narsinh Mehta bhajan popularized by Gandhi covers a full octave. It is slightly more advanced than the first two. Practice the ascending portion toward upper-Sa separately as this range extension can be initially challenging for beginners.</p>

      <h2>4. Hanuman Chalisa Opening Verse</h2>
      <p>Uses: Sa Re Ga Ma Pa. Melody: S R G M, G R S. The simple pentatonic melody of the Hanuman Chalisa opening makes it ideal for beginners. The repeated phrases build confidence and muscle memory quickly. This bhajan also introduces the concept of melodic variations within a repeating structure.</p>

